solution.p:
 When y=0, y'=\frac{0}{2}-1=-1.


 When y=2, y'=\frac{2}{2}-1=0.


 When y=3, y'=\frac{3}{2}-1=0.5.





The small red lines have varying slopes. The red lines on points with y-coordinate 2 have slopes of  0; this matches y' when y=0, as we saw above.
The red lines on points with y-coordinate 0 have slopes of approximately -1;
again, this matches what we found for y' when y=0.



The red lines correspond to a tiny section of y(x), if y(x) passes through that point. So, we can sketch a possible curve y(x) satisfying the equation by starting somewhere, then following the slopes.



For example, suppose we start at the origin.

